        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity: Figure 1 shows the calculated brightness temperature differences Delta-T between models with and without HC5N created using our extensively benchmarked NEMESIS radiative transfer code (Irwin et al 2008). Differences are given in Table 1. To ensure a positive detection in at least two lines, we base our sensitivity requirement on the second strongest line of the two lines targeted with differences of 3K at 0.976MHz resolution. To attain our minimum S/N of 30 means we require a noise level of 0.1K at 0.976MHz resolution. Absorption by atmospheric water vapour is low in band 4 and to achieve our target rms of 0.1K, the AOT calculated a total observation time of 2.25hrs, assuming 0.8" resolution, nominal water vapour conditions and including all overheads. 

Imaging requirements: Titan's projected angular diameter is 0.8". Therefore, at 155GHz Titan can be effectively observed with any of the six Cycle 2 array configurations. The most compact configuration C34-1 will have an angular resolution/synthesised beam size of 2.3", which will give a disk-averaged spectrum. Observations will also be effective up to the most extended array configuration C34-6 (0.24" synthesised beam), as Titan's diameter is smaller than the limiting maximum angular size for all array configurations. 
If Titan's disk has uniform emission, S/N is independent of the spatial resolution, although if emission is larger in the north as expected, partially resolving the polar region should result in a somewhat improved S/N. However, as Titan's disk is only just resolvable in Cycle 2, a disk-averaged spectrum is more appropriate at this stage, and we request a minimum spatial resolution of 0.8", leaving flexibility to take the observation with any array configuration. Large u-v coverage is not required.

Correlator setup: Emission features from our nitrile species of interest occur between 153--159GHz, which can all be covered by a single observational setup and local oscillator tuning.
To allow for different line widths we will use the four available basebands as follows:
two spectral windows at 0.488MHz channel spacing (1.875GHz bandwidth, 0.976MHz spectral resolution) to observe the entire range;
and two spectral windows at 0.122MHz channel spacing (0.496GHz bandwidth, 0.244MHz spectral resolution) for maximum S/N on the narrow HC5N lines. 
The higher resolution spectral windows will be centred on emission features andwill allow more accurate determination of vertical profiles.
Dual polarisation will be used to maximise S/N.

Calibration: Default calibration.

Bandpass accuracy: Spectral feature / continuum ratios are expected to be well below 1000 in Band 4.

Scheduling/Time constraints: We have a mild timing constraint in that Titan must be well separated from Saturn to avoid contamination of the spectra. The antenna FOV at 160GHz is 32" and Titan's orbit is 15.9 days with a radius of 200". Therefore, to avoid any possible contamination from Saturn we request the observation takes place when Titan is at least 3xFOVs (96") from the edge of Saturn (equivalent to 106" from Saturn's centre). This means that Titan should be free from Saturn contamination for 65% of its orbit, giving many regularly spaced observing opportunities. A precise ephemeris can be provided during Phase 2 planning if required.

Science Team: NAT, PGJI, CAN, and RdK have extensive experience modelling Titan's atmosphere in the sub-mm.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
