    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>This proposal aims to provide the first spectroscopic detections of complex nitrile HC5N in Titan's atmosphere. Model predictions show that spectral features of HC5N should all be observable by ALMA at high signal-to-noise with a single observation setup. This would be the first time that HC5N have ever been detected in Titan's middle atmosphere. By combining the results with upper-atmosphere Cassini INMS in-situ mass spectrometer measurements and examining the line-shapes, information about the vertical profiles could be determined. This would help reveal the photochemical production pathways involved as well as the origin of a mysterious nitrile sink suggested by recent Cassini observations. Current residual enrichment of nitriles at northern latitudes means that Cycle 2 observations will be unusually sensitive to this compound compared to future cycles. Also, the 155GHz observation frequency is affected little by atmospheric water vapour and Titan's small projected size means that observations could be taken with any array configuration - resulting in a flexible and straight forward observation.</prp:abstract>
